1. Introduction¶

"Doesn't need to be long" Goal, we want to determine if around the world people are being given a fair salary and if not determine what costs are contributing to this observation.

We would expect that as the cost of living increases, so too does the salary of an individual(reggression).

We want to know how poeple are being treated around the world, if payemnt meets the price required of living. Are people being fairly given a living wage(categorical) what places have the most cost and least salary, what places have the least cost and most salary.

State that we will do this using the Data Science Pipeline

  1. Data collection/curation + parsing (if necessary)
  2. Data management/representation
  3. Exploratory data analysis
  4. Hypothesis testing
  5. Communication of insights attained

3. Dataset¶

The objective of this tutorial is to explore and understand the Cost of Living between different countires and how they relate to each other, as well as to determine what factors play the largest role/ a method of predicting the GCL/Salary.

To this end we have obtained the following dataset from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mvieira101/global-cost-of-living

# Random forest Regression
# Split the data into training/testing data using a 80:20 split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(index_df['salary_index'].to_numpy().reshape(-1, 1), index_df['mortgage_index'])

# Tunning of hyper paramemters
# In order to determine the hyperparameters we will be using RandomizedSearchCV with 10-fold cross-validation
# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
print(random_grid)
rf = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = RandomForestRegressor(), param_distributions = random_grid, cv = 10, verbose=2, n_jobs = 4)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(rf.best_params_)

# Create set of predicted values based on the test data
pred = rf.predict(X_test)

plt.scatter(X_test, y_test, color = 'blue') 
 
# plot predicted data
plt.plot(X_grid, regressor.predict(X_grid),
         color = 'green')
plt.title('Random Forest Regression')
plt.xlabel('Position level')
plt.ylabel('Salary')
plt.show()

# Check Error
errors = abs(pred - y_test)
print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))
